duce, have lost their jobs, or have been forced into higher levels of debt. In this thought-provoking challenge to mainstream views, the authors provide a cohesive narrative that shows how the class wars of rising inequality are a threat to the global economy and international peace—and what we can do about it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCommerce. 0aInternational economic relations. 0aSocial classes. 0aWorking class. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aPettis, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2020 Englishz978311070479208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2020z9783110704624oZDB-23-DBV08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069231040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300252750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300252750.jpg  a978-3-11-069231-0  YUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070479-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DBVb2020  aZDB-23-DGGb2020